    {
      "abstract": "• FOWT mechanical model fidelity was examined for TMD calibration. • Omnidirectional TMD (OTMD) efficacy was tested under operating conditions. • OTMD performance was examined under a gust-induced fault. • Fatigue and vibration mitigation was examined considering environmental variability. • Effect of aerodynamic damping on TMD effectiveness was assessed. This paper investigates the mitigation of bidirectional vibration and induced short-term fatigue in a 5MW barge-type floating offshore wind turbine (FOWT) subjected to stochastic misaligned wind and wave loadings. To address this challenge, a passive omnidirectional tuned mass damper (OTMD) integrated within the barge floater is proposed as a vibration suppression strategy. First, a comprehensive dynamic analysis was conducted under realistic environmental conditions using the coupled aero-hydro-servo-elastic simulation tool OpenFAST in order to identify the critical vibration modes of the FOWT. Next, TMD calibration techniques/mechanical models were reviewed to determine the relevant mechanical model and calibration technique to be used for the mitigation of bidirectional dynamic responses. The performance of the calibrated OTMD was evaluated under both operational and parked conditions taking into account the environmental variability. Mitigation performance under operational condition was assessed considering vibration, short-term fatigue and nacelle acceleration peak for long-crested (unidirectional) and short-crested (multidirectional) wave excitations. Additionally, the OTMD effectiveness during extreme parked scenarios triggered by gust-induced fault followed by emergency shutdown was evaluated, focusing on vibration and peak response attenuation. The observed mitigation performance was found to be strongly influenced by aerodynamic damping, as reflected in the OTMD motion within the barge floater. Overall, the results demonstrate the efficacy of using a passive omnidirectional TMD for reducing bidirectional dynamic responses in a 5 MW barge-type FOWT.",
